					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Por=
tion of a solid that lies between two parallel planes cutting the solid</di=
v>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For other us=
es, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frustum_(disambiguation)" =
class=3D"mw-disambig" title=3D"Frustum (disambiguation)">Frustum (disambigu=
ation)</a>.</div>
<div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><div class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner=
" style=3D"width:442px;max-width:442px"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"t=
single" style=3D"width:201px;max-width:201px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" sty=
le=3D"height:198px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pentagonal_frustum.svg" class=3D"mw-file-de=
scription"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/1/15/Pentagonal_frustum.svg/250px-Pentagonal_frustum.svg.png" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"199" height=3D"199" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"500" data-file-height=3D"500"></a></span></div></div><div cl=
ass=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:237px;max-width:237px"><div class=3D"thumbim=
age" style=3D"height:198px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Usech_kvadrat_piramid.png" class=3D=
"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wik=
ipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Usech_kvadrat_piramid.png/250px-Usech_kvadrat_pir=
amid.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"235" height=3D"199" class=3D"mw-file-=
element" data-file-width=3D"650" data-file-height=3D"550"></a></span></div>=
</div></div><div class=3D"trow" style=3D"display:flex"><div class=3D"thumbc=
aption">Pentagonal frustum and square frustum</div></div></div></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry"=
>geometry</a>, a <span title=3D"Latin-language text"><span lang=3D"la" styl=
e=3D"font-style: normal;"><b>frustum</b></span></span> (<a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Latin =
language">Latin</a> for 'morsel');<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frustum#cite_note-3"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
(<abbr title=3D"plural">pl.</abbr>: <b>frusta</b> or <b>frustums</b>) is th=
e portion of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedron" title=
=3D"Polyhedron">solid</a> (normally a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Pyramid_(geometry)" title=3D"Pyramid (geometry)">pyramid</a> or a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Cone (geometry)">cone</a>) that lies between two <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_planes" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Par=
allel planes">parallel planes</a> cutting the solid. In the case of a pyram=
id, the base faces are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygonal" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polygonal">polygonal</a> and the side faces =
are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoidal" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Trapezoidal">trapezoidal</a>. A <b>right frustum</b> is a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_pyramid" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Right pyramid">right pyramid</a> or a right cone <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truncation_(geometry)" title=3D"Truncation (geometr=
y)">truncated</a> perpendicularly to its axis;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frustum#cite_note-4=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> otherwise, it is an <b>oblique frustum</b>.=20
</p><p>In a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truncated_cone" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Truncated cone">truncated cone</a> or <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truncated_pyramid" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Truncated pyramid">truncated pyramid</a>, the truncation plane is <em>=
not</em> necessarily parallel to the cone's base, as in a frustum.
</p><p>If all its edges are the same length, then a frustum becomes a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prism_(geometry)" title=3D"Prism (geome=
try)">prism</a> (possibly oblique or/and with irregular bases).
</p>
<div style=3D"clear:both;" class=3D""></div>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Elements,_special_cases,_an=
d_related_concepts"><span id=3D"Elements.2C_special_cases.2C_and_related_co=
ncepts"></span>Elements, special cases, and related concepts</h2><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFrustum&amp;action=3Dedit&=
amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Elements, special cases, and relate=
d concepts"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>A frustum's axis is that of the original cone or pyramid. A frustum is c=
ircular if it has circular bases; it is right if the axis is perpendicular =
to both bases, and oblique otherwise.
</p><p>The height of a frustum is the perpendicular distance between the pl=
anes of the two bases.
</p><p>Cones and pyramids can be viewed as degenerate cases of frusta, wher=
e one of the cutting planes passes through the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Apex_(geometry)" title=3D"Apex (geometry)">apex</a> (so that t=
he corresponding base reduces to a point). The pyramidal frusta are a subcl=
ass of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prismatoid" title=3D"Prisma=
toid">prismatoids</a>.
</p><p>Two frusta with two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congrue=
nce_(geometry)" title=3D"Congruence (geometry)">congruent</a> bases joined =
at these congruent bases make a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bi=
frustum" title=3D"Bifrustum">bifrustum</a>.
</p>
<div style=3D"clear:both;" class=3D""></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Formulas">Formulas</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFrustum&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Formulas"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Volume">Volume</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFrustum&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Volume"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Frustum_with_symbols.svg" class=3D"mw-file-de=
scription"><img alt=3D"Pyramidal frustum" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.o=
rg/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Frustum_with_symbols.svg/250px-Frustum_with=
_symbols.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"280" class=3D"=
mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"301" data-file-height=3D"337"></a><figc=
aption>Pyramidal frustum</figcaption></figure><p>The formula for the volume=
 of a pyramidal square frustum was introduced by the ancient <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Egyptian mathematics">Egyptian mathematics</a> in what is called the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moscow_Mathematical_Papyrus" title=
=3D"Moscow Mathematical Papyrus">Moscow Mathematical Papyrus</a>, written i=
n the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/13th_dynasty" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"13th dynasty">13th dynasty</a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</=
abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=891850 BC</span>):
</p><dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span =
class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: non=
e;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\display=
style V=3D{\frac {h}{3}}\left(a^{2}+ab+b^{2}\right),}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>V</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>h</mi>
            <mn>3</mn>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow>
            <msup>
              <mi>a</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
            <mo>+</mo>
            <mi>a</mi>
            <mi>b</mi>
            <mo>+</mo>
            <msup>
              <mi>b</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle V=3D{\frac {h=
}{3}}\left(a^{2}+ab+b^{2}\right),}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/db9c0d9cccca8d1b242b400eeb3f737252cb5ee2" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.838ex; width:22.856ex; height:5.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle V=
=3D{\frac {h}{3}}\left(a^{2}+ab+b^{2}\right),}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span>=
 and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> are=
 the base and top side lengths, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">h</span> is the height.
</p><p>The Egyptians knew the correct formula for the volume of such a trun=
cated square pyramid, but no proof of this equation is given in the Moscow =
papyrus.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume" title=3D"Volume=
">volume</a> of a conical or pyramidal frustum is the volume of the solid b=
efore slicing its "apex" off, minus the volume of this "apex":
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e V=3D{\frac {h_{1}B_{1}-h_{2}B_{2}}{3}},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>V</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <msub>
                <mi>h</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>1</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
              <msub>
                <mi>B</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>1</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
              <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
              <msub>
                <mi>h</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
              <msub>
                <mi>B</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
            </mrow>
            <mn>3</mn>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle V=3D{\frac {h=
_{1}B_{1}-h_{2}B_{2}}{3}},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/274eda13f2f375aa829f2e9ca03623c75366e135" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.838ex; width:19.632ex; height:5.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle V=
=3D{\frac {h_{1}B_{1}-h_{2}B_{2}}{3}},}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>B</i><sub>1</sub></span> and <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>B</i><sub>2</sub></span> are the base and top areas, and <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i><sub>1</sub></span> and <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>h</i><sub>2</sub></span> are the perpendicular heights from the apex=
 to the base and top planes.
</p><p>Considering that
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\frac {B_{1}}{h_{1}^{2}}}=3D{\frac {B_{2}}{h_{2}^{2}}}=3D{\frac {\sqrt {=
B_{1}B_{2}}}{h_{1}h_{2}}}=3D\alpha ,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <msub>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>1</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msub>
            <msubsup>
              <mi>h</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>1</mn>
              </mrow>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msubsup>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <msub>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msub>
            <msubsup>
              <mi>h</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msubsup>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <msqrt>
              <msub>
                <mi>B</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>1</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
              <msub>
                <mi>B</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
            </msqrt>
            <mrow>
              <msub>
                <mi>h</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>1</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
              <msub>
                <mi>h</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B1<!-- =CE=B1 --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\frac {B_{1}=
}{h_{1}^{2}}}=3D{\frac {B_{2}}{h_{2}^{2}}}=3D{\frac {\sqrt {B_{1}B_{2}}}{h_=
{1}h_{2}}}=3D\alpha ,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4bf26bdb6ff9229b34668f12607f371604f14fc8" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.838ex; width:27.147ex; height:6.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
frac {B_{1}}{h_{1}^{2}}}=3D{\frac {B_{2}}{h_{2}^{2}}}=3D{\frac {\sqrt {B_{1=
}B_{2}}}{h_{1}h_{2}}}=3D\alpha ,}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>the formula for the volume can be expressed as the third of the product =
of this proportionality, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-i=
